00:00:56.030 --> 00:00:58.530
Now how many of you sang "Old
MacDonald" when you were kids,

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:00.370
or maybe you're singing
it with your own children?

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:01.890
So when we walk
into the supermarket

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:03.540
and look around
pictures on products,

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.685
it looks like Old MacDonald's
farm is still around today.

00:01:05.685 --> 00:01:07.440
We see all these
rolling green hillsides,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:09.000
all those happy cows.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.080
But unfortunately, this is not
what farming is like anymore

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:14.520
in the United States.

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:17.340
Rather than old MacDonald,
this is what we have today.

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:20.310
Factory farms are technically
known as Concentrated Animal

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.810
Feeding Operations, or CAFOs.

00:01:22.810 --> 00:01:25.540
It's a practice of keeping
thousands-- tens of thousands,

00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:27.900
hundreds of thousands--
of animals in confinement

00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:29.520
for their entire lives.

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:34.750
This is done to produce the most
product for the most profit.

00:01:34.750 --> 00:01:36.340
Before we go any
further, does anyone

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:38.890
want to guess how many
animals are bred and killed

00:01:38.890 --> 00:01:40.615
for food every year
in the United States.

00:01:40.615 --> 00:01:42.490
If you don't already
know the answer-- anyone

00:01:42.490 --> 00:01:43.790
want to take a guess?

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:44.966
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:01:44.966 --> 00:01:47.340
KATIE CANTRELL: OK, so
pretty close-- so yeah,

00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:49.130
there's actually nine billion.

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:51.550
There between nine
and 10 billion animals

00:01:51.550 --> 00:01:53.830
raised and killed for
food every single year

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:55.150
in the United States, alone.

00:01:55.150 --> 00:01:57.880
This is just land animals,
not even counting fish.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:00.340
So there are more farmed
animals in the United States

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.460
than there are people
on the entire planet.

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:05.290
Now of these nine
billion animals,

00:02:05.290 --> 00:02:06.790
what percentage of
them do you think

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:08.350
are raised on
factory farms rather

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:11.190
than on those nice, small,
Old MacDonald type farms?

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:11.950
AUDIENCE: 80%.

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:13.120
KATIE CANTRELL: 80%?

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:17.710
About 99%-- so 99% of
meat that you see nowadays

00:02:17.710 --> 00:02:19.570
in restaurants or
supermarkets is

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:22.480
going to be coming from
these factory farms.

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:24.640
Now if we've heard the
term factory farming,

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:26.912
it's usually in the
context of animal welfare.

00:02:26.912 --> 00:02:28.870
And that's not what we'll
be focusing on today,

00:02:28.870 --> 00:02:31.540
but I do briefly want to
discuss what conditions

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:33.899
look like on factory
farms, because that's also

00:02:33.899 --> 00:02:36.190
what contributes to most of
the environmental problems,

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:37.084
as well.

00:02:37.084 --> 00:02:38.500
And I think it
helps to understand

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:40.210
the mindset of
factory farming, which

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:43.480
is really summed up best by
"National Hog Farmer Magazine."

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:45.940
They said, "the breeding
sow"-- which is a mother pig--

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:47.530
"should be thought
of and treated

00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:50.020
as a valuable piece of
machinery whose function

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:53.200
is to pump out baby pigs
like a sausage machine."

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.450
So these are no longer
thought of as living,

00:02:55.450 --> 00:02:56.790
sentient creatures.

00:02:56.790 --> 00:03:00.010
They're thought of as
units of production.

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:01.450
It is this mindset
that allows us

00:03:01.450 --> 00:03:03.940
to treat farmed animals in
ways that we would never dream

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:05.742
of treating our dogs or cats.

00:03:05.742 --> 00:03:07.450
So again, the hallmark
of factory farming

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:09.670
is this intensive confinement.

00:03:09.670 --> 00:03:12.370
The animals spend their entire
lives, sometimes confined

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:17.920
in cages or crates so small that
they can't even turn around.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:19.960
Other industries, like
the turkey industry,

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:23.530
they're kept by the thousands
inside of these sheds.

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:26.350
So this, obviously,
causes extreme problems

00:03:26.350 --> 00:03:27.700
for animal welfare.

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:30.700
They can't engage in even the
most basic of natural behavior.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.410
But it is also this
overcrowding that

00:03:32.410 --> 00:03:34.460
causes the environmental
issues, as well.

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:36.100
So for the rest of
the presentation,

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:37.558
you have to keep
in mind that these

00:03:37.558 --> 00:03:39.750
are what conditions look
like on factory farms,

00:03:39.750 --> 00:03:43.740
where 99 percent of
meat is coming from.

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:45.930
Now one question that
frequently comes up

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:47.430
is what about the
labels that we see

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:48.870
on products that seem
to indicate they're

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:50.010
coming from better places?

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.500
So I want to quickly go
through what those mean.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:54.120
I'll start with cage-free.

00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:56.460
This is a picture of
a cage-free egg farm.

00:03:56.460 --> 00:03:58.710
Now, it's true, these
hens aren't in cages,

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:01.200
but it's not exactly what we
imagine when we see the term

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:03.390
cage-free, when we see
those happy-looking chickens

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:04.920
on the front of the carton.

00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:06.210
So it really means just that.

00:04:06.210 --> 00:04:07.470
They're not in cages,
but they're still

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:09.240
kept by the tens
of thousands inside

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:13.330
of these industrial sheds
for their entire lives.

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:15.270
Unfortunately, conditions
on free-range farms

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:16.110
are very similar.

00:04:16.110 --> 00:04:17.700
So technically, it
means the animals

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:19.980
must have "access
to the outdoors,"

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:22.530
but there are no real
enforced specifications

00:04:22.530 --> 00:04:23.739
for what that means.

00:04:23.739 --> 00:04:26.280
And there are a lot of loopholes
as well, that a lot of farms

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:28.530
get away with, keeping
their animals confined

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:30.870
by the tens of thousands
inside of the sheds.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:32.940
But if there is "access
to the outdoors,"

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:35.906
like a tiny little door that
opens onto a dirt patch,

00:04:35.906 --> 00:04:37.530
it can technically
count as free-range,

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:42.120
even if not a single animal ever
actually steps foot outside.

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.340
Now to give you a
real world example,

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:47.070
the wording on the left is from
a package of Judy's Eggs, which

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:50.280
is a popular organic,
free-range brand from right here

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:51.570
in northern California.

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:53.790
It says these hens are
raised in wide open spaces

00:04:53.790 --> 00:04:56.400
in Sonoma Valley, where they
are free to roam, scratch,

00:04:56.400 --> 00:04:57.290
and play.

00:04:57.290 --> 00:04:59.280
Well, on the right, you
can see an aerial photo

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:01.009
of what Judy's Farm
actually looks like.

00:05:01.009 --> 00:05:03.300
Those are those industrial
sheds with tens of thousands

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:04.140
of chickens.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:05.432
There aren't any birds outside.

00:05:05.432 --> 00:05:07.181
And the purple that
you see in front there

00:05:07.181 --> 00:05:09.390
is a manure pit, which
we'll be talking about much

00:05:09.390 --> 00:05:12.000
more in a few minutes.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.004
Now, Judy's actually
settled a lawsuit

00:05:14.004 --> 00:05:15.420
with the Animal
Legal Defense Fund

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:18.510
for misleading consumers with
the claims on their packaging.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:20.100
So they have
changed the wording,

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.680
but they're still certified
free-range and organic.

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:25.875
And in fact, they re-brand under
several different brand names,

00:05:25.875 --> 00:05:28.500
which is a very common practice
to make consumers think they're

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:31.290
coming from these nice, little,
individual family farms,

00:05:31.290 --> 00:05:34.451
when they're coming from the
same source-- these factory

00:05:34.451 --> 00:05:34.950
farms.

00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:37.158
So they sell under Judy's,
Uncle Eddy's, Rock Island,

00:05:37.158 --> 00:05:38.010
Gold Circle.

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:40.710
They're also a leading
supplier for Whole Foods 365

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:42.390
brand and Organic Valley.

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:44.730
So unfortunately, even
some of the most respected

00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:46.770
organic, free-range
brands are, in fact,

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:50.145
sourcing from factory farms.

00:05:50.145 --> 00:05:52.020
The final term that you
might see is 'humane,

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:54.120
and this has no legal
meaning whatsoever.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:57.030
The USDA does not regulate
the term 'humane,' nor do they

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:59.610
regulate the term 'natural,'
so any company can put these

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:00.640
on any product.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.520
It's really just a
marketing gimmick.

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:04.560
And it's unfortunate
because these companies

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:06.604
are taking advantage
of consumers' desire

00:06:06.604 --> 00:06:08.770
to buy products that are
coming from a better place.

00:06:08.770 --> 00:06:10.680
We don't want animals
to be mistreated.

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:14.160
We don't want to impact the
environment in negative ways.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:16.380
But unfortunately,
this is usually

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:18.600
just used as a mechanism
to increase the price

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:21.880
when they're still coming
from factory farms.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.730
Animal agriculture is one of
the single most destructive

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:26.560
industries on the planet.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:28.730
I know this can seem a
little bizarre if we're still

00:06:28.730 --> 00:06:29.980
imagining Old McDonald's farm.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.350
What could be so bad
about Old McDonald, right?

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:34.965
So I'm going to
walk you through it.

00:06:34.965 --> 00:06:36.340
So again, keep in
mind that there

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:39.814
are nine billion animals raised
and killed for food every year.

00:06:39.814 --> 00:06:41.980
And this is where most of
the environmental problems

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:44.350
stem from-- it's the sheer
number of animals that

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:48.070
are required to make enough meat
for 300 million plus Americans

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:51.232
to eat meat every single
day, often with every meal.

00:06:51.232 --> 00:06:52.690
And the problems
come from the fact

00:06:52.690 --> 00:06:55.780
that these are nine billion
living, breathing, eating,

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:57.370
pooping animals.

00:06:57.370 --> 00:07:00.120
Now, they're eating
primarily corn and soy.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.680
When we imagine farmers
and farmland in the US,

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:08.860
we, I think, imagine growing
crops to feed to people, right?

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:11.260
But in the United States,
over half of all farmland

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:13.720
is planted with corn and
soy, and most of that

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:17.660
is going to feed not people,
but to animals on factory farms.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:21.150
This is a problem for
several different reasons.

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:24.470
One is that animals are actually
a very inefficient source

00:07:24.470 --> 00:07:25.440
of food.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:28.640
So imagine that you are
raising an animal for food.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:30.355
From the day that
that animal is born,

00:07:30.355 --> 00:07:32.980
till the day that you slaughter
it, you have to feed it, right?

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:35.360
So that's days, weeks, months,
potentially even years,

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:38.550
that you're giving this
animal food every single day.

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:40.160
So if you add up all
the food that you

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:42.740
give to that animal over
the course of its lifetime,

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:45.800
it ends up being anywhere
from 2 to 15 times more

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:48.770
food than the amount of food you
get from eating that animal's

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:49.910
flesh.

00:07:49.910 --> 00:07:52.370
The latest studies have found
that if we cut global meat

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:54.300
consumption in
half, and we use all

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:56.570
that farmland to grow fruits
and veggies for people

00:07:56.570 --> 00:07:58.430
to eat directly,
rather than growing

00:07:58.430 --> 00:08:01.130
that corn and soy to feed
to animals on factory farms,

00:08:01.130 --> 00:08:02.630
we could feed
every single person

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:06.590
on earth today, plus an
extra two billion people.

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:08.420
So we hear a lot of
talk about how are we

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:10.770
going to feed the growing
global population?

00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:12.320
And in fact, we
could do it easily

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:14.390
if we were using our
land more efficiently,

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:17.510
but eating lower
on the food chain.

00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:20.700
This land use is a huge
problem globally, as well.

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:23.510
Meat production is actually
the leading cause of the Amazon

00:08:23.510 --> 00:08:25.320
rain forest being cut down.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:27.800
We can see that here in this
infographic from the Center

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:29.450
for Biological Diversity.

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:32.179
Every minute, there are
two acres of rain forest

00:08:32.179 --> 00:08:34.730
clear cut to make grazing
land for beef cattle

00:08:34.730 --> 00:08:36.620
or land to grow
corn and soy to feed

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:39.710
to animals on factory farms.

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:42.526
This is also a problem in
the United States, as well.

00:08:42.526 --> 00:08:45.150
Oftentimes, people think I don't
want to support factory farms,

00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:47.020
so I'm going to buy
free-range beef.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:49.870
Now there are a couple of
different problems with this.

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:52.090
One is that actually,
most beef cattle

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:55.640
are free-range for the first
8 to 10 months of their lives.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:56.980
So if you drive--

00:08:56.980 --> 00:08:59.200
especially in Marin,
Petaluma, that area--

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:00.970
you might see these
bucolic-looking cattle

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:03.020
grazing on hillsides,
and it looks very nice.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:04.570
But most of those
cattle are then

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:06.580
shipped to industrial
feedlots, where they're

00:09:06.580 --> 00:09:09.490
fed corn and soy intensively
for the last few months

00:09:09.490 --> 00:09:12.880
of their lives to fatten them
up to reach market weight.

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:14.800
The other big problem
is that while there

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:17.050
are certain ecosystems
that do benefit

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:19.440
from having grazing
ruminant animals,

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:21.250
there is a limit
to how many animals

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:24.160
that land can sustain-- it's
called a carrying capacity.

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:26.080
And when you exceed
that, you start

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:28.330
to have these very serious
ecological problems,

00:09:28.330 --> 00:09:31.060
and that's what we're
seeing across the West, now.

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:34.720
So cattle are being
grazed on public land,

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:39.580
so the government is basically,
subsidizing this grass in order

00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:41.344
to graze these
free-range cattle,

00:09:41.344 --> 00:09:42.760
but the Bureau of
Land Management,

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:45.100
which manages this
land, is not ensuring

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:47.800
that it's being managed
properly to prevent

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:49.190
these environmental problems.

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:51.196
So you have too many
cattle on this land,

00:09:51.196 --> 00:09:52.570
so they're eating
everything that

00:09:52.570 --> 00:09:53.695
comes up out of the ground.

00:09:53.695 --> 00:09:56.260
They're eating what would
grow into shrubs and trees

00:09:56.260 --> 00:09:59.410
to provide habitat
for native animals,

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:02.360
this also causes soil
erosion, impacts waterways--

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:04.750
so a lot of different
devastating impacts

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:07.080
of overgrazing.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:10.420
And to make matters worse, there
is a very secretive government

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:12.510
agency called Wildlife Services.

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:14.200
They're a part of the USDA.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:17.620
And in 2015, they killed
over three million animals,

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:20.080
mostly at the
request of ranchers.

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:23.620
So they're killing off predators
like wolves, bears, coyotes,

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:26.530
foxes, mountain lions that
could kill the livestock.

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:29.280
They're killing off prairie
dogs and ground squirrels that

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:31.960
could dig holes that the
cattle could fall into,

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:34.030
even rounding up and
killing buffalo--

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:36.250
so native ruminant animals,
because they're competing

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:37.720
with the cattle for feed.

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:40.630
So we're destroying these
entire native ecosystems

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:45.510
in order to make them suitable
for free-range cattle.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:47.760
Now another big problem
with all of these animals

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:50.499
and all of these crops is that
they're very water intensive.

00:10:50.499 --> 00:10:52.290
Now when we think about
ways to save water,

00:10:52.290 --> 00:10:54.250
what are some things
that come to mind?

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:56.590
What are ways we're told
we can help save water?

00:10:56.590 --> 00:10:58.540
AUDIENCE: Less
water in the shower.

00:10:58.540 --> 00:11:00.331
KATIE CANTRELL: Yeah,
take shorter showers,

00:11:00.331 --> 00:11:01.547
right-- that's a classic one.

00:11:01.547 --> 00:11:03.630
Turn off the tap when you
brush your teeth, right?

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:04.520
Water your lawn less.

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:07.440
So all of these suggestions
focus on our direct water

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:08.250
usage.

00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:10.830
In this next video clip
from the movie "Cowspiracy,"

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:13.380
we'll see how this compares to
the water impact of our food

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:13.880
choices.

00:11:14.814 --> 00:11:15.480
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.250
- I found out that
one quarter pound

00:11:17.250 --> 00:11:21.360
hamburger requires over 660
gallons of water to produce.

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:23.985
Here I've been taking short
showers trying to save water,

00:11:23.985 --> 00:11:26.940
and to find out just eating
one hamburger is the equivalent

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:29.970
of showering two entire months.

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:32.700
So much attention is given to
lowering our home water use,

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:34.890
yet domestic water
use is only 5%

00:11:34.890 --> 00:11:36.630
of what is consumed
in the US, versus

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:38.970
55% for animal agriculture.

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:41.910
That's because it takes upwards
of 2,500 gallons of water

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:43.857
to produce one pound of beef.

00:11:43.857 --> 00:11:44.690
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:45.740
KATIE CANTRELL:
The single best way

00:11:45.740 --> 00:11:47.540
that we can help save
water on a daily basis

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:48.720
is through our food choices.

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:51.066
So the numbers they use
there are on the high end,

00:11:51.066 --> 00:11:52.940
but even the more
conservative estimates show

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:55.700
that switching from a hamburger
to a veggie burger, just one

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:59.000
single time opting for a veggie
burger instead of a hamburger,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.130
you save as much water as not
showering for one entire month.

00:12:04.130 --> 00:12:08.510
So all that water, all of
this corn and soy, also

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:11.840
a lot of hormones,
pesticides, antibiotics--

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:13.730
are fed to these
nine billion animals.

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:16.430
It goes through their
system and then what happens

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:18.170
to food after we digest it?

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:20.066
It comes out as poop.

00:12:20.066 --> 00:12:21.440
Farm animals in
the United States

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:24.980
produce 130 times as much
poop as the entire US

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:26.240
human population.

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.730
And there is very little
waste infrastructure

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:29.850
for factory farms.

00:12:29.850 --> 00:12:30.842
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:30.842 --> 00:12:32.500
