00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:45.210
The animals we eat are grown
inside giant hidden factories.

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:49.300
Since 2012, I've been
secretly planning a project

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:53.500
to expose these factory farms
using the highest tech spy

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:55.630
equipment available--

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:56.860
drones.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:59.020
This video provides
just a sample

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:02.720
of what I saw during only
a few days of filming.

00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:04.160
[BUZZING]

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:11.300
You're looking at a
lake of toxic feces

00:13:11.300 --> 00:13:15.110
and urine, the size of
four football fields.

00:13:15.110 --> 00:13:17.990
That's because thousands
upon thousands of pigs

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:20.260
are inside of these buildings.

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:24.080
Their waste falls through
slats in the concrete floor

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:29.500
and it's flushed directly into
this giant open-air cesspool.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.000
How many of these kinds
of factories are there?

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.260
In North Carolina alone,
there are over 2,000

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:39.020
and the consequences
are disastrous.

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.760
- The waste falls
through the floors.

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:47.000
It's flushed out into an
open pit, like a cesspool.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.570
It's easy for a
big hog operation

00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:54.060
to have as much waste
as a medium-sized city.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:58.720
Of course, the pit will fill
up, so it has to be emptied,

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:02.330
and they're emptied by
spraying the liquid waste.

00:14:02.330 --> 00:14:04.040
- Yes, you heard that right.

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.550
- If you're familiar
with a garden sprayer,

00:14:06.550 --> 00:14:09.050
they are gigantic
versions of that.

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:12.500
So they're making
droplets, fine mists,

00:14:12.500 --> 00:14:18.530
out of this liquid waste,
and that can drift down wind

00:14:18.530 --> 00:14:20.360
into the neighboring
communities.

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:25.030
- I shut my hog operation
down and I got out of it.

00:14:25.030 --> 00:14:28.220
And I couldn't--

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:31.060
I just couldn't do
another person that way,

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:32.720
to make them smell that.

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.050
It is a cesspool that you
put feces and urine in,

00:14:36.050 --> 00:14:39.090
a hole in the ground that
you dump toxic waste in.

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:42.110
And I've seen dead hogs in
them, and stuff like that.

00:14:42.110 --> 00:14:46.040
- People can't open their
windows, they can't go outside.

00:14:46.040 --> 00:14:47.360
- I've seen it.

00:14:47.360 --> 00:14:48.470
I've talked to the people.

00:14:48.470 --> 00:14:50.250
I've seen the little children.

00:14:50.250 --> 00:14:52.730
They say, mom and daddy, why
we got to smell this stuff?

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:56.620
You get stories like, I
can't hang my clothes out.

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:59.050
Feces and urine odor comes
by and attaches itself it

00:14:59.050 --> 00:14:59.846
to your clothes.

00:14:59.846 --> 00:15:01.220
And then people
are saying, we're

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:03.210
scared to invite neighbors.

00:15:03.210 --> 00:15:06.410
- It can, I think, very
correctly be called

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:09.680
environmental racism or
environmental injustice--

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:14.360
that people of color,
low income people,

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:16.654
bear the brunt of
these practices.

00:15:16.654 --> 00:15:18.570
- This is where they
spray animal waste on us.

00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:20.470
This is about eight feet
from my mother's house.

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:21.920
- What is it like
when the mist--

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:24.861
- It's like you
think it's raining.

00:15:24.861 --> 00:15:25.360
- Really?

00:15:26.649 --> 00:15:27.690
- You think it's raining.

00:15:27.690 --> 00:15:29.660
We don't open the
doors or the windows,

00:15:29.660 --> 00:15:31.020
but the odor still comes in.

00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:32.540
It takes your breath away.

00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:34.340
Then you start gagging,
you get headaches.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:38.180
- There are a number of studies
of asthma and asthma symptoms,

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:40.700
particularly in children,
near these facilities.

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:45.200
Among adults, there are
reports of several types

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:47.140
of upper respiratory symptoms.

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:51.560
These pollutants are affecting
people's blood pressure.

00:15:51.560 --> 00:15:53.390
- Who's responsible
for all this?

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:56.620
Smithfield Foods,
specifically, the subdivision

00:15:56.620 --> 00:15:59.240
Murphy Brown, which
controls the factory

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:02.900
farms shown in all of the
drone footage in this video.

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:06.140
Smithfield is by far,
the largest pork producer

00:16:06.140 --> 00:16:07.700
in the entire world.

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:09.710
And inside these
buildings, there

00:16:09.710 --> 00:16:11.620
is something else entirely.

00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:13.220
- Pigs are really
intelligent animals.

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:15.020
They are more
intelligent than dogs,

00:16:15.020 --> 00:16:16.700
they are more
intelligent than cats.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:18.650
In the average pig
barn, there could

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:22.040
be hundreds, if not thousands,
of pigs crammed into this

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.440
one sprawling indoor space.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:27.310
Their entire life is spent
standing on concrete floors.

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:30.230
Mother pigs are locked in
metal cages so small that they

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:34.100
literally cannot even turn
around for months at a time.

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:36.170
- This is not a partisan issue.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:39.230
We are all opposed to
children being made sick,

00:16:39.230 --> 00:16:42.530
to animals being abused, and to
everyday people's lives being

00:16:42.530 --> 00:16:46.010
ruined by the stench of
cesspools in their backyards.

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:49.100
These thousands of
lakes of toxic waste

00:16:49.100 --> 00:16:51.800
must be among the most
bizarre and disturbing

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:55.900
environmental phenomenon that
have ever confronted America.

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:57.730
And they've been
kept well-hidden

00:16:57.730 --> 00:17:01.747
from the public for long enough.

00:17:01.747 --> 00:17:03.244
[BUZZING]

00:17:16.407 --> 00:17:17.240
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:18.650
KATIE CANTRELL: So
you've just seen

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:20.316
what happens to all
of this waste-- it's

00:17:20.316 --> 00:17:21.530
fairly shocking, right?

00:17:21.530 --> 00:17:24.227
And for urban consumers, meat
starts at the supermarket,

00:17:24.227 --> 00:17:25.310
it starts at a restaurant.

00:17:25.310 --> 00:17:28.190
We don't ever have
to see or experience

00:17:28.190 --> 00:17:29.150
the real impacts of it.

00:17:29.150 --> 00:17:31.580
So it's usually these rural,
low-income communities,

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:33.470
often communities
of color, that bear

00:17:33.470 --> 00:17:35.600
the brunt of the rest
of our meat consumption.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:37.225
They're the ones who
have to be exposed

00:17:37.225 --> 00:17:39.930
to this environmental
pollution on a daily basis.

00:17:39.930 --> 00:17:42.020
The other huge problem
with all of these animals

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:45.860
and all of this waste
is climate change.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.800
A report from the United Nations
found that animal agriculture

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:52.280
creates more greenhouse gas
emissions than all the planes,

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:56.910
trains, and cars in the entire
world all added up together.

00:17:56.910 --> 00:17:59.690
Part of the reason for this is
that ruminant animals like cows

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:01.850
and sheep, lambs--

00:18:01.850 --> 00:18:04.670
actually burp methane,
which is 20 times worse

00:18:04.670 --> 00:18:06.879
for climate change
than carbon dioxide.

00:18:06.879 --> 00:18:09.170
The poop from all of these
different types of animals--

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:11.780
chickens, pigs, all the
ones that we've seen--

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:14.870
releases nitrous oxide,
which is 300 times worse

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:17.750
for climate change
than carbon dioxide.

00:18:17.750 --> 00:18:20.300
And there are also all of the
impacts of that deforestation.

00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:22.716
When you consider the whole
lifecycle of everything that's

00:18:22.716 --> 00:18:24.726
required to produce the
meat, the deforestation

00:18:24.726 --> 00:18:26.350
also plays a large
role because they're

00:18:26.350 --> 00:18:29.510
cutting down forests that would
otherwise be absorbing CO2.

00:18:29.510 --> 00:18:32.660
So when you factor in all
of these things together,

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:36.104
you see that our food choices
are also the single best way

00:18:36.104 --> 00:18:37.520
that we can help
shrink our carbon

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:40.430
footprint on a daily basis,
just like our water footprint.

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:43.460
So one study found that not
eating meat just one day a week

00:18:43.460 --> 00:18:45.650
saves some more greenhouse
gas emissions than buying

00:18:45.650 --> 00:18:49.610
local food 100% of the time.

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:52.640
A different study found that if
everyone in the United States

00:18:52.640 --> 00:18:55.520
ate no meat or cheese
just one day a week,

00:18:55.520 --> 00:18:58.460
it would be like not
driving 91 billion miles,

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:01.790
or taking 7.6 million
cars off the road.

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:04.040
So we can think about, what
are the chances that we're

00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:06.860
going to convince seven million
people to sell their cars

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:08.330
and never drive again--

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:10.320
probably not going
to happen, right?

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:14.180
Whereas getting people to not
eat meat just one day a week--

00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:16.310
choosing a PB&amp;J instead
of a turkey sandwich

00:19:16.310 --> 00:19:18.560
and a veggie burrito
instead of a beef burrito--

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:20.870
it's one of the easiest
and most effective ways

00:19:20.870 --> 00:19:24.620
that we can help
stop climate change.

00:19:24.620 --> 00:19:28.610
And in fact, there's more
and more scientific evidence

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:32.510
showing that we cannot keep
climate change to a level

00:19:32.510 --> 00:19:35.540
that's conducive to human
civilization without addressing

00:19:35.540 --> 00:19:38.000
the carbon footprint
of agriculture.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.180
So this study found that the
agriculture-related emissions

00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:44.092
alone, if we continue
our current practices,

00:19:44.092 --> 00:19:45.800
especially as the
global population grows

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:48.080
and demand for meat
goes up worldwide,

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:50.960
then agriculture alone
will take up almost all

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:54.600
of the global carbon
budget by 2050.

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.980
So this means that even if we
got every other industry down

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:01.190
to carbon neutral, but we
left agriculture the same,

00:20:01.190 --> 00:20:04.640
we would still be hitting
that two-degree target.

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:07.970
So the only scenario that
would reduce emissions in 2050

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:10.690
compared to 2009 levels is
what they call the healthy diet

00:20:10.690 --> 00:20:13.190
scenario, which is switching
to significantly more

00:20:13.190 --> 00:20:16.160
plant-based protein.

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:19.220
And as an added benefit,
eating more plant-based protein

00:20:19.220 --> 00:20:23.480
also has positive impacts
on the health of citizens

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:25.470
and on health care costs.

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:28.760
So if Americans transition
to a plant-based diet,

00:20:28.760 --> 00:20:30.980
not only would it reduce
food-related greenhouse gas

00:20:30.980 --> 00:20:35.930
emissions by 79%, we could
also avoid 460,000 deaths

00:20:35.930 --> 00:20:40.040
and save $289 billion in health
care costs and climate change

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:41.180
costs.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:43.940
So one of the reasons that
people eat so much meat

00:20:43.940 --> 00:20:46.400
is that it seems
cheap, but that's

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:48.330
because the true costs
of it are externalized.

00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:51.410
So we don't have to see the
environmental costs, the health

00:20:51.410 --> 00:20:53.180
care costs, when
we go to the store,

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:54.470
when we go to the restaurant.

00:20:54.470 --> 00:20:58.280
But as taxpayers, we are
actually paying the true cost.

00:20:58.280 --> 00:21:00.500
And the most effective
way to reverse that

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:03.980
is to transition to a
more plant-based diet.

00:21:03.980 --> 00:21:06.180
The basic solution
is very simple.

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:07.280
We have to eat less meat--

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:09.290
that's really what
it boils down to.

00:21:09.290 --> 00:21:12.170
And different organizations,
world leaders,

00:21:12.170 --> 00:21:14.390
are starting to catch
on to this and starting

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:16.680
to encourage people to switch
to plant-based protein.

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:18.864
So the United Nations
Environmental Program

00:21:18.864 --> 00:21:20.780
has urged first world
citizens to cut our meat

00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:23.910
consumption in half, become
what they call "demitarians."

00:21:23.910 --> 00:21:25.850
The Stockholm International
Water Institute

00:21:25.850 --> 00:21:27.740
has gone even further
and said that we

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:30.230
need to limit animal-based
foods to just 5%

00:21:30.230 --> 00:21:31.820
of our total daily calories.

00:21:31.820 --> 00:21:33.530
Right now, they
make up about 30%

00:21:33.530 --> 00:21:34.850
of the standard American diet.

00:21:34.850 --> 00:21:38.330
So they said we need to
eat just 1/6 as much meat

00:21:38.330 --> 00:21:39.620
as we currently are.

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:41.820
And they've warned that
if we do not do this,

00:21:41.820 --> 00:21:44.120
then we will be faced with
food and water shortages

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:46.550
worldwide that could
lead to civil war.

00:21:46.550 --> 00:21:48.230
So the stakes are
about as high as they

00:21:48.230 --> 00:21:49.688
get when we're
talking about things

00:21:49.688 --> 00:21:52.370
like climate change,
global famine,

00:21:52.370 --> 00:21:54.830
and all this can be
impacted directly

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:57.080
through our food choices.

00:21:57.080 --> 00:21:59.750
Now a big challenge is
how do you get people

00:21:59.750 --> 00:22:01.939
interested in eating less meat?

00:22:01.939 --> 00:22:03.980
There are a lot of reasons
that people eat meat--

00:22:03.980 --> 00:22:05.839
it tastes good, it's
cheap, it's convenient,

00:22:05.839 --> 00:22:07.880
it's part of our culture,
it's part of our habit.

00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:10.040
And so now, different
organizations,

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:12.770
nonprofits, as well as many
different food start-ups,

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:15.230
especially in the Bay
Area, are working on ways

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:17.000
to get people
excited about eating

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.340
more plant-based protein.

00:22:19.340 --> 00:22:22.340
One initiative that's been very
successful is Meatless Mondays.

00:22:22.340 --> 00:22:24.710
This was actually started
by Johns Hopkins University

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:26.480
as a public health initiative.

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:28.970
As we saw a few slides
ago, health care costs

00:22:28.970 --> 00:22:31.790
are hugely impacted by the
amount of animal protein

00:22:31.790 --> 00:22:33.530
that Americans
currently consume.

00:22:33.530 --> 00:22:36.480
Many of the leading causes of
death-- cancer, heart disease,

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:37.730
diabetes, stroke--

00:22:37.730 --> 00:22:40.910
are directly related to eating
too much animal protein.

00:22:40.910 --> 00:22:44.565
So they figured if people
eat even 1/7 less meat--

00:22:44.565 --> 00:22:46.862
if people are not eating
meat one day a week--

00:22:46.862 --> 00:22:48.570
then it will really
help people's health.

00:22:48.570 --> 00:22:50.600
And many other organizations
have jumped on board

00:22:50.600 --> 00:22:52.641
and said it's a great way
to help the environment

00:22:52.641 --> 00:22:53.720
and animals, as well.

00:22:53.720 --> 00:22:55.340
And even for
die-hard meat lovers,

00:22:55.340 --> 00:22:58.310
the idea of not eating
meat just one day a week

00:22:58.310 --> 00:23:00.380
is something that
seems very doable.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:02.000
And currently, a
third of Americans

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.150
report trying to participate.

00:23:05.150 --> 00:23:07.890
Green Monday is also another
really successful program

00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:10.400
that is similar to Meatless
Monday, but really focused

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:13.190
on those environmental
impacts, emphasizing the fact

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:16.040
that the best way to
go green is by eating

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:17.426
more plant-based protein.

00:23:17.426 --> 00:23:18.800
It's actually
based in Hong Kong,

00:23:18.800 --> 00:23:20.720
and they've had
tremendous success

00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:24.770
in shifting the entire
city's eating habits

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:27.560
by having a really positive,
empowering campaign,

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:31.010
emphasizing that eating
green, choosing veg options,

00:23:31.010 --> 00:23:33.620
is a very effective
step to take.

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:36.780
And Green Monday emphasizes that
it's not a one-size-fits-all.

00:23:36.780 --> 00:23:40.124
So oftentimes, people are
deterred from taking a step

00:23:40.124 --> 00:23:41.540
because they think
that they won't

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:44.600
be able to be perfectly
100% vegetarian or vegan,

00:23:44.600 --> 00:23:46.740
and so people get
dissuaded and they give up.

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:48.575
But as a Green
Monday shows, there

00:23:48.575 --> 00:23:50.950
are a number of different ways
that we can go about this.

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:54.050
So whether that's routine-based,
one day a week-- so

00:23:54.050 --> 00:23:55.730
Green Monday or Meatless Monday.

00:23:55.730 --> 00:23:57.320
You can do every day for lunch.

00:23:57.320 --> 00:24:00.560
Eat a vegetarian
or vegan lunch--

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:02.927
just one meal a day, it's
pretty doable for most people.

00:24:02.927 --> 00:24:04.760
But if you do that,
then a third of the time

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:06.260
you'll be eating veg.

00:24:06.260 --> 00:24:09.470
It can also be portion-based,
so decreasing the amount of meat

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:12.580
they're eating, increasing the
amount of plant-based protein,

00:24:12.580 --> 00:24:15.830
vegetarian foods on your plate.

00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:18.800
Or it can be impact-based,
so pledging to only order

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:21.620
veggie burgers instead of
hamburgers from now on.

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:24.020
There are many different
ways that we can play around

00:24:24.020 --> 00:24:25.790
with our food
choices and increase

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:28.040
the amount of plant-based
foods that we're eating.

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:31.400
And it, again, is one of the
single most effective actions

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:34.230
that we can take.

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:36.800
There are also some very
exciting tech solutions

00:24:36.800 --> 00:24:38.970
that are in the works right
now, namely, clean meat.

00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:42.770
So clean meat involves
extracting stem cells

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:46.460
from animal tissue, culturing
those, and then, basically,

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:48.950
growing meat tissue in the lab.

00:24:48.950 --> 00:24:51.710
And then layering that to
produce hamburgers, chicken

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:52.370
nuggets.

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:53.660
So it is actually meat.

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:55.670
I mean, it is animal
tissue and it's

00:24:55.670 --> 00:24:58.790
based on medical technology
used to grow human skin cells

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:00.050
to graph on to burn victims.

00:25:00.050 --> 00:25:02.420
But they're actually
growing meat.

00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:04.580
And this is successful.

00:25:04.580 --> 00:25:06.320
Memphis Meats has produced--

00:25:06.320 --> 00:25:08.540
I think just about a month ago--

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:11.104
they had the first tastings of
clean chicken and duck meat.

00:25:11.104 --> 00:25:12.770
And there are a few
other companies that

00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:14.690
are working on beef, as well.

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:19.020
And this is extremely more
efficient than factory farming.

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:22.850
So clean meat uses
99% less land,

00:25:22.850 --> 00:25:25.670
produces 96% less
greenhouse gas emissions,

00:25:25.670 --> 00:25:27.610
and uses 96% less water.

00:25:27.610 --> 00:25:29.912
And there's a really
great organization

00:25:29.912 --> 00:25:31.370
called the Good
Food Institute that

00:25:31.370 --> 00:25:34.940
is working to help encourage
the science behind clean meat

00:25:34.940 --> 00:25:37.070
and policy around
clean meat, as well.

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:38.717
So according to
latest estimates,

00:25:38.717 --> 00:25:40.550
it should be on the
market within about four

00:25:40.550 --> 00:25:41.330
to five years.

00:25:41.330 --> 00:25:42.620
Again, the technology
is there, it's

00:25:42.620 --> 00:25:44.286
just a matter of
scaling it so that it's

00:25:44.286 --> 00:25:47.000
cost-competitive with
factory farm meat.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.400
But I think this is one of
the most hopeful developments.

00:25:49.400 --> 00:25:52.550
If we can replace fast
food meat with clean meat,

00:25:52.550 --> 00:25:56.370
then we will see drastic
impacts on the environment,

00:25:56.370 --> 00:25:59.750
and obviously, for
animals, as well.

00:25:59.750 --> 00:26:01.442
But the good news
is that you don't

00:26:01.442 --> 00:26:03.650
have to wait four or five
years to make a difference.

00:26:03.650 --> 00:26:05.900
There are a number
of other start-ups,

00:26:05.900 --> 00:26:08.930
all based right around
here, that are working

00:26:08.930 --> 00:26:11.660
on creating foods that have
the same taste textures that we

00:26:11.660 --> 00:26:14.570
love, but they are made
from more sustainable

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:15.600
plant-based sources.

00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:17.997
So as Biz Stone
said, "these guys

00:26:17.997 --> 00:26:20.330
are coming at the meat analog
industry not as a novelty.

00:26:20.330 --> 00:26:22.371
They're coming at it from
the big science angle."

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:26.840
These products are not made for
vegetarian markets, anymore,

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:28.340
they're not made
for a niche market.

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:31.040
They're getting the top
chefs, top food scientists,

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:33.290
to create products that
are really delicious

00:26:33.290 --> 00:26:35.500
and satisfying for
die-hard meat lovers.

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:38.600
So you have companies like
Beyond Meat, Impossible

00:26:38.600 --> 00:26:40.160
Foods, which makes the burger--

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:41.810
"the burger that
bleeds," as it's

00:26:41.810 --> 00:26:43.726
been getting a lot of
attention in the press--

00:26:43.726 --> 00:26:45.984
Hampton Creek Foods, which
makes Just Mayo, cookies,

00:26:45.984 --> 00:26:47.900
salad dressings, and all
of these products you

00:26:47.900 --> 00:26:50.480
can read articles,
see interviews online.

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:51.980
They do blind taste
tests and people

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:53.570
can't tell the difference.

00:26:53.570 --> 00:26:57.050
So if the main reason
that we're eating meat

00:26:57.050 --> 00:26:59.050
is because it tastes
good, it's fantastic

00:26:59.050 --> 00:27:00.800
news that there are
now products available

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:02.810
that have that same
taste, the same texture,

00:27:02.810 --> 00:27:04.726
but they're better for
us, better for animals,

00:27:04.726 --> 00:27:08.510
better for the environment,
so it's really a win-win.

00:27:08.510 --> 00:27:10.060
And this is a top-growing trend.

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:13.160
This is really the direction
that the market is moving.

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:18.170
So "Food Navigator Magazine,"
Mintel, "The Nutrition Business

00:27:18.170 --> 00:27:18.800
Journal"--

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:21.140
I mean, they've all
documented that Americans

00:27:21.140 --> 00:27:23.046
are eating more and
more plant-based foods,

00:27:23.046 --> 00:27:24.920
they're interested in
it from a health angle,

00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:27.410
from an environmental angle,
and this is consistently

00:27:27.410 --> 00:27:30.680
one of the fastest growing
sectors of the food system.

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:33.200
As a result, an even
more exciting trend,

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:35.360
is that meat and dairy
companies are actually

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:36.980
starting to jump on board.

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:40.640
So even Tyson Chicken-- their
CEO, the CEO of Tyson Chicken--

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:44.150
said the plant-based protein
is the way of the future.

00:27:44.150 --> 00:27:47.130
And dairy companies are also
investing in plant-based dairy.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:50.300
So Dannon Yogurt, the parent
company that makes Dannon,

00:27:50.300 --> 00:27:52.934
bought White Wave, which makes
Silk soy milk and almond milk.

00:27:52.934 --> 00:27:55.100
And they're shifting a lot
of their marketing budget

00:27:55.100 --> 00:27:57.890
away from marketing dairy
foods towards marketing

00:27:57.890 --> 00:27:59.120
plant-based foods.

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:01.490
So we see this very
positive feedback cycle,

00:28:01.490 --> 00:28:04.280
where the more that we
vote with our dollars

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:07.160
and we buy these products,
the more appealing

00:28:07.160 --> 00:28:10.210
that food sector becomes to
businesses, they invest in it.

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:12.302
Then those products are
more widely available,

00:28:12.302 --> 00:28:14.510
they're cheaper, they're
more accessible, and so more

00:28:14.510 --> 00:28:16.130
and more people
start buying them.

00:28:16.130 --> 00:28:19.490
And as we've seen, especially
with products like almond milk,

00:28:19.490 --> 00:28:22.200
then they start to take up a
larger and larger market share,

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:24.980
and as a result, there are
fewer animals bred and killed

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:26.390
for food every year.

00:28:26.390 --> 00:28:29.060
So often times, people say,
but I'm just one person.

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:31.160
What difference do my
food choices really make?

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:35.090
But we really can have a very
direct impact on this industry.

00:28:35.090 --> 00:28:38.120
And especially at a
time when federal policy

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:40.940
is increasingly
frustrating and alarming--

00:28:40.940 --> 00:28:43.910
there's zero chance of federal
action on climate change

00:28:43.910 --> 00:28:45.540
within these next few years--

00:28:45.540 --> 00:28:48.440
so this is even more
important, that we can really

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:50.390
directly impact this
industry, and have

00:28:50.390 --> 00:28:55.640
a real impact on climate change
through our daily food choices.

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:58.129
And it's really never been
easier or at least tastier

00:28:58.129 --> 00:28:59.420
to eat these plant-based foods.

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:02.210
So Gardien products are
probably my favorite.

00:29:02.210 --> 00:29:03.832
They have these
great, crispy tenders.

00:29:03.832 --> 00:29:05.540
And they're actually
owned by the company

00:29:05.540 --> 00:29:06.730
that makes Hungry Man dinners.

00:29:06.730 --> 00:29:08.271
So again, we see
these meat companies

00:29:08.271 --> 00:29:10.340
starting to invest in
plant-based products.

00:29:10.340 --> 00:29:12.800
Almond milk is available
at every supermarket.

00:29:12.800 --> 00:29:14.660
Ben and Jerry's now
has seven flavors

00:29:14.660 --> 00:29:17.100
of almond milk-based ice cream.

00:29:17.100 --> 00:29:19.820
So we see, again, it's
a growing trend, which

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:23.990
is great for all of us because
it makes it so easy to do.

00:29:23.990 --> 00:29:27.500
And again, you don't have
to be 100% vegetarian

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:29.442
to order a veggie burger
or a veggie burrito.

00:29:29.442 --> 00:29:31.400
You don't have to be
totally vegan all the time

00:29:31.400 --> 00:29:34.100
to put almond milk in your
cereal instead of cow milk.

00:29:34.100 --> 00:29:37.400
It's not about being
all-or-nothing, 100% perfect.

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:39.950
It's about looking at the
impacts of our food choices

00:29:39.950 --> 00:29:42.170
and deciding what we want
our money to support.

00:29:45.340 --> 00:29:48.130
And the other good news is
that, again, this really

00:29:48.130 --> 00:29:49.300
has a direct impact.

00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:53.860
So supply and demand applies,
demand has been going down--

00:29:53.860 --> 00:29:56.230
since 2007, demand has dropped.

00:29:56.230 --> 00:29:57.850
And as a result,
there are 400 million

00:29:57.850 --> 00:29:59.680
fewer animals bred
and killed for food

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:01.690
now than there
were back in 2007,

00:30:01.690 --> 00:30:03.940
as a direct result of people
like you and me deciding

00:30:03.940 --> 00:30:05.630
to eat less meat.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:08.410
So remember that every time
you decide not to eat an animal

00:30:08.410 --> 00:30:10.240
product, you are taking
action against one

00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:14.430
of the most destructive
industries on the planet.

