00:31:19.980 --> 00:31:21.396
KATIE CANTRELL:
So the question is

00:31:21.396 --> 00:31:24.480
what's the relationship between
the animal products consumed

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:26.710
in the US and what is
consumed around the world?

00:31:26.710 --> 00:31:29.670
So, I mean, it's a pretty
complicated relationship.

00:31:29.670 --> 00:31:34.320
It depends on the industry,
but roughly 15% of products

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:35.830
here are exported.

00:31:35.830 --> 00:31:38.799
So Americans do hav-- now we
have the second highest meat

00:31:38.799 --> 00:31:39.840
consumption in the world.

00:31:39.840 --> 00:31:42.900
We were actually
passed by Australia.

00:31:42.900 --> 00:31:45.210
But we do eat most of
those products here.

00:31:45.210 --> 00:31:46.890
Some of it is exported.

00:31:46.890 --> 00:31:49.020
We do import some
products, as well.

00:31:49.020 --> 00:31:50.814
And a lot of these
companies are now--

00:31:50.814 --> 00:31:52.230
they started in
the United States,

00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:54.270
but they're now
multinational corporations.

00:31:54.270 --> 00:31:57.630
And actually, Smithfield, which
is the largest pork producer,

00:31:57.630 --> 00:32:00.600
was bought, basically--
a majority stake--

00:32:00.600 --> 00:32:02.680
was bought by a Chinese company.

00:32:02.680 --> 00:32:06.750
And so now, we are starting to
see an increase in pork exports

00:32:06.750 --> 00:32:07.290
to China.

00:32:07.290 --> 00:32:10.140
So now Americans
are having to deal

00:32:10.140 --> 00:32:12.420
with the environmental
pollution,

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:14.220
and these products are exported.

00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:17.190
Another huge issue
is alfalfa feed.

00:32:17.190 --> 00:32:20.670
Alfalfa is the most intensive
crop, in terms of water.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:24.580
And Saudi Arabia and
other countries are now--

00:32:24.580 --> 00:32:27.090
they're importing alfalfa
from the United States.

00:32:27.090 --> 00:32:28.960
So they're basically
importing water.

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:32.250
So this is a huge problem,
because a lot of that alfalfa

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:34.800
is grown in Southern
California and Arizona,

00:32:34.800 --> 00:32:37.350
and parts of the country that
are facing these droughts.

00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:40.080
And our water is actually being
exported to support the dairy

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:42.870
industry in the Middle East.

00:32:42.870 --> 00:32:45.480
And the US is also--

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:49.290
we have set this example
that if you're well-off,

00:32:49.290 --> 00:32:50.730
the lifestyle that we've--

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:54.150
that other people want to
emulate as their income grows,

00:32:54.150 --> 00:32:56.850
is that meat is an
integral part of living.

00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:58.920
Well, eating meat
every day shows

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:01.560
that you are middle
class or upper class.

00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:04.800
And so there's a
cultural impact, as well.

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:07.020
And I'm hopeful
that we can change

00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:09.480
that, if we can show the United
States is saying, actually,

00:33:09.480 --> 00:33:11.200
